<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12112e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12112e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12112e"> 112(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sapiential</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Nous ne pouvons gu&egrave;re juger des &eacute;tudes que fit Colomban que d&apos;apr&egrave;s ses oeuvres; mais cette enqu&ecirc;te, forc&eacute;ment incompl&egrave;te, nous donne d&eacute;j&agrave; une haute id&eacute;e de sa science. Il conna&icirc;t &agrave; fond l&apos;Ecriture, surtout les Psaumes, les livres <mark>sapientiaux</mark> et le Nouveau Testament; il cite saint J&eacute;r&ocirc;me (<cite>Liber de Viris illustribus; lib. In Ezechiel</cite>) <br><font color="green">[We can hardly judge Colomban&apos;s studies except through his works; but this research, incomplete in any case, gives us great esteem for his learning. He knew Scripture completely, especially the Psalms, the <mark>wisdom</mark> literature and the New Testament; he cites saint Hieronymus (<cite>Liber de Viris illustribus; lib. In Ezechiel</cite>)]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 14n1</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Sapiential: characterised by wisdom, hence it is usually applied to the &lsquo;wisdom&rsquo; books of the Bible &mdash; Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Canticles, Wisdom, Ecclesiasticus &mdash; as well as to some of the similar, non-canonical writings. </mm> </dd></dl>
